The two ROC panels illustrate the core finding of this study. In the 1980s, all four curves sit close together — attitude-based and demographic models perform at a similar level, with AUC values ranging from 0.70 to 0.76. Neither track clearly dominates the other. By the 2020s, the picture has changed completely. The attitude-based curves (purple and green) have pulled far ahead, reaching AUC ≈ 0.93, while the demographic curves (orange) remain around 0.77. The gap that was barely visible in the 1980s has become the defining feature of the 2020s panel. Demographic characteristics — race, education, income, religion — still carry some predictive signal, but they are a much weaker guide to party identification than what someone believes about abortion, government spending, or racial equality. This pattern directly contradicts H2: rather than demographics becoming increasingly predictive over time, they have been overtaken by attitudes as the primary organizing dimension of American partisanship.

